standing Mysticism -- tPART II. HOW TRADITION SHAPES BOTH THE MYSTICAL EXPERIENCE AND THE MYSTIC'S RESPONSES TO IT -- tBook Three: Mysticism Among the Oglala Lakota: The Visions of Black Elk -- t16. The Historical Setting of Black Elk’s Life -- t17. Black Elk’s Great Vision -- t18. Three Major Characteristics of Black Elk’s Great Vision -- t19. Principal Characteristics of Lakota Power -- t20. Black Elk’s Criteria of Discernment -- t21. Black Elk’s Response to His Great Vision -- t22. Black Elk’s Dog Vision -- t23. Black Elk and the Ghost Dance -- t24. Black Elk’s Conversion to Christianity -- tBook Four: The Mysticism of Saint Teresa of Avila -- t25. Why Study Saint Teresa? -- t26. A Biographical Sketch of Saint Teresa of Avila -- t27. Saint Teresa’s Recollective Technique -- t28. Distinctive Features of Saint Teresa’s Prayer States -- t29. Medieval Influences on Saint Teresa’s Mysticism -- t30. Saint Teresa’s Criteria of Discernment -- t31. The Contextuality of the Most Elevated States of Spiritual Perfection and Mystical Awareness -- tConclusion -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis sweeping study of mysticism by Jess Hollenback considers the writings and experiences of a broad range of traditional religious mystics, including Teresa of Avila, Black Elk, and Gopi Krishna. It also makes use of a new category of sources that more traditional scholars have almost entirely ignored, namely, the autobiographies and writings of contemporary clairvoyants, mediums, and out-of-body travelers. This study contributes to the current debate about the contextuality of mysticism by presenting evidence that not only are the mystic's interpretations of and responses to experiences culturally and historically conditioned, but historical context and cultural environment decisively shape both the perceptual and affective content of the mystic's experience as well.Hollenback also explores the linkage between the mystic's practice of recollection and the onset of other unusual or supernormal manifestations such as photisms, the ability to see auras, telepathic sensitivity, clairvoyance, and out-of-body experiences. He demonstrates that these extraordinary phenomena can actually deepen our understanding of mysticism in unexpected ways.A unique feature of this book is its in-depth analysis of ";empowerment,"; an important phenomenon ignored by most scholars of mysticism. Empowerment is a peculiar enhancement of the imagination, thoughts, and desires that frequently accompanies mystical states of consciousness. Hollenback shows its cross-cultural persistence, its role in constructing the perceptual and existential environments within which the mystic dwells, and its linkage to the fundamental contextuality of mystical experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMysticismvComparative studies. 0aParapsychologyxReligious aspects. 7aRELIGION / Mysticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027107268540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271072685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271072685/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK